	<tr>
		<td colspan="3" class="text">
			<span id="lbl_quick_summary">See-and-be-seen is the hallmark of this ultra-hip Ian Schrager/Philippe Starck San Francisco creation that’s loaded with edgy finishes and a whimsical flair sure to impress. </span>
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="3"><img src="/destinations/images/spacer.gif" height="20" width="572" alt="" border="0"></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="392" valign="top">
			<img src="/destinations/images/shermans_review.gif" height="14" width="131" alt="" border="0">
			<font class="text">
				<p><span id="lbl_review">This completely renovated, larger-than-life property beckons trendsetters, fashionistas, and celebrities galore with glamorous digs nestled in the Theater District, just two blocks from Union Square. The new Clift, remodeled in 2001 blends contemporary style with surrealist magic &#150; thanks to designer Philippe Starck, of course. The lobby’s soaring ceilings, contrasting colors, and extra-large furniture (of the sort you’d expect to find in a giant’s liar) exude an out-of-this-world vibe. The hotel’s famous Redwood Room bar is one of the city’s hottest night spots and blends the traditional with the ultra modern. Original redwood paneling and massive bar &#150; supposedly carved out of one giant redwood tree &#150; are offset by chic, contemporary furniture and digital artwork.
<br><br>
The Clift’s 375 guest rooms are in sharp contrast to the over-the-top lobby and public spaces. Instead of fanciful, over-the-top d&#233;cor, the rooms all share a simple design of light and airy colors. All though on the small side, monochromatic units have a soothing feel with luxurious fabrics, blond-wood furnishings, translucent orange acrylic nightstands, floor-to-ceiling mirrors, and many with great views of the city and the Golden Gate Bridge. All boast cable TVs, VCRs, mini-bars, CD and DVD players, and high-speed Internet access. 
</span></p>
			</font>

